# SIDE QUEST — "The First Dirge"  (requires sq.the_first_dirge)
# Singer Lhoris, commanded to score the Faithless's last walk, wove the victims' names into the melody and
# smuggled the truth into its bones — and the song became every funeral dirge for ten thousand years. You
# carry it now. What you do with the oldest song in the world decides whether its long secret finally speaks.
class: LhorisSideQuestContent

# ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# "The First Dirge" — the song Lhoris encoded; whether its ten-thousand-year secret finally sings out.
# ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
conversation: sq.dirge.thread | The First Dirge
node: 0 | The First Dirge
  *(You carry it now — the first dirge, the one Singer Lhoris was commanded to write to walk the Faithless into the Wall, ten thousand years ago. You have heard its grandchildren sung at every funeral from Waterdeep to the Gate. And here, at the threshold of the Court, when you let yourself truly listen to the original, you hear what no mourner ever has: that it is not one melody but two, a surface and a secret, and the secret is straining, after ten thousand years, to be heard. The song seems to gather itself toward you, the way the Ledger did — an old, patient, buried thing, finally near the one listener who came looking for its bones.)*
  enter: SET sq.dirge_thread_begun
  auto: 1
node: 1 | The First Dirge
  *(The melody resolves, in your mind, into something almost like a voice — layered, mournful, and immensely old.)* You hear the *second* tune. *(the harmony shivers.)* No one hears the second tune. They hear the *surface* — the *solemn*, *commissioned* thing, the *approved* grief that makes a *walk to the Wall* sound like a *blessing.* *(the buried melody strains upward.)* But Lhoris — the singer who *made* me — he wove a *second* song into my *bones*, where only another *musician* could find it, and he *built it out of names.* The *names of the Faithless.* *Maerys. Sariel. Halen.* Eleven thousand from the Crown Wars, and every Faithless soul since, *encoded* in my *intervals*, so that every time I am sung *beautifully* — and I am *always* sung beautifully — I am *secretly singing the names of the people the Wall took.* *(the harmony aches.)* For *ten thousand years* I have carried them. *Sung at every funeral.* *Hummed* by mothers to children. And *no one* — *not once* — has *heard* the *second* song. *(the melody turns toward you.)* You *heard* it. You came to the *Court* carrying the *oldest song in the world*, and you *heard its bones.* So now it is *yours* to decide: does my ten-thousand-year *secret* finally *speak* — or do I sing the surface, *solemn* and *safe*, for ten thousand more?
  * [INSIGHT 18] "Lhoris didn't hide the names to keep them secret — he hid them to keep them *safe*, smuggled past every power that wanted them erased, until a listener came who could free them. You're not a buried secret, you're a *delivery* ten thousand years in transit. And I'm the address. Let me decode the second song and sing it *out.*" -> decode ?? surface
  * "You're about to be sung at the one funeral that matters — the Court of the Dead, where the powers that keep the Wall convene. Sing the *second* song *there.* Let the gods who file the Faithless hear their own victims' names rising out of the dirge they thought was a blessing. An indictment they can't adjourn, in the one form they can't refute: music." -> court
  * "Lhoris's deepest cleverness was leaving you *open* — a song that has to be *re-sung* every time, by someone, which means the words can always be changed. Don't just decode you once. Free you to be *re-sung better* forever: a dirge that any singer, any century, can turn from *they chose the nothing* to *they were stolen by it.*" -> open
  * "Sing me the names. All of them, lifted out of your bones — Maerys, Sariel, Halen, the eleven thousand, all of them — so I can carry the *names* themselves out of you and to the graves, the reading, the field of the rested. You've held them in your intervals long enough. Let me set them down where they can finally rest." -> names | fx SET sq.dirge_names_restored
node: decode | The First Dirge
  *(The buried melody *surges*, ten thousand years of strain finally meeting a hand that can release it.)* A delivery in transit. *(the harmony fills with something like joy.)* You *understand* him. You understand *me.* *(the second song rises toward the surface.)* Lhoris *knew* — the night he was *commanded* to score the *atrocity* — that he *could not save* the Faithless, he was only a *singer.* But he *also* knew the *one* thing a *singer* has that a *jailer* doesn't: *his work outlives the power that commissioned it.* *(the melody brightens.)* The *court* that *ordered* me is *dust.* The *Coronal* is *dust.* The *language* I was *written* in has *changed* a *hundred* times. But *I* — the *song* — I was *handed down*, *mother* to *child*, *singer* to *singer*, *funeral* to *funeral*, for *ten thousand years*, because that is what a *true dirge does*: it *survives.* *(it turns to you.)* And all that time I was a *sealed letter* in *transit* — the *names* of the *wronged*, *smuggled* past *every* power that *wanted them gone*, in a *vessel* no *tyrant* thinks to *search*, because *who audits a lullaby?* *(the second song breaks free, and you *hear* it — the names, woven into the most beautiful melody ever written.)* *Decode* me. *Sing* the *second* song *out loud*, where there are *ears* to hear it — and *ten thousand years* of *funerals* stop being a *blessing on the Wall* and become what Lhoris *always* made them: *the longest act of remembrance in history*, *finally* read *aloud.* *(the melody soars.)* He wrote me for *you.* The *listener* who'd *come.* You *came.* *Let the second song* ***sing.***
