node: leave_open | The First Dirge
  *(The melody ripples, content, settling into its truest nature.)* Leave me *open.* *(the harmony turns over, at peace.)* A *decoded* song is a *fact* — *fixed*, *finished*, *true* for the *moment* it's *sung* and then *over.* *(the second song shivers.)* But an *open* song is a *future.* *(it rises.)* You're *right* that the *deepest* freedom isn't *decoding* me *once*, in *one* room, for *one* set of *ears* — it's *handing* the *world* a *dirge* it can *keep* *re-singing* *kinder*, *century* by *century*, *each* generation *changing* one *more* word, *each* singer *turning* the *verdict* a *little* further — until the *song* that once *sealed* the *Faithless* into the *Wall* is the *song* that *overturns* it, *sung* by *people* who don't even *know* they're *finishing* what Lhoris *started.* *(the melody soars, unfileable, eternal.)* That is the *one* thing the *Wall* can *never* do, *Returned. A Wall is a fact that needs no one and so can never* change. *I am a* question *that needs a* singer *every single time — and a thing re-chosen forever can be re-chosen* better, *forever.* *(it quiets, luminous.)* *Free* me to be *sung* *new.* Let the *oldest* song in the *world* stay *young* — *open*, *unfinished*, *always* one *singer* away from *kinder* — for *as long* as there are *mourners* and *throats* and *grief* that *needs* a *tune.* That outlasts *every* power that ever tried to *fix* my *meaning.* *That* is how a *song* *defeats* a *Wall*: not by *being* *louder*, but by *never* being *done.*
  enter: SET sq.dirge_freed_to_change, SET act2.cataloguing_defeats_the_wall, SET act3.truth_smuggled_in_song, appr.ilfaeril +5
  auto: close
node: surface | The First Dirge
  *(The melody dims, the second song sinking back into the bones where it has hidden for ten thousand years.)* You hear the bones, but you will not *free* them. *(the harmony quiets, patient.)* That is — *no failing.* The *song* has *waited* ten thousand years; it can *wait* longer. *(it settles.)* I will *sing* the *surface* — *solemn*, *approved*, *safe* — at *every* funeral, as I *always* have, and the *names* will stay *woven* in my *intervals*, *un-decoded*, *un-sung-aloud*, *carried* but not yet *delivered.* *(the melody recedes.)* Come *back* when you can *bear* what the *second* song *costs* to *free* — for to *sing* the *Faithless* *out loud* is to *defy* the *powers* that *walled* them, and *defiance* has a *price*, and you need not *pay* it *today.* *(it hums, the secret sealed.)* I am *patient*, *Returned.* I am the *oldest* song in the *world.* *Patience* is the *one* thing I have *more* of than *anyone.* The *bones* will *keep.* They have *kept* this *long.* *(and the first dirge subsides into its surface melody, beautiful and solemn and secretly grieving, waiting — as it has waited ten thousand years — for a listener brave enough to free what it carries.)*
  auto: close
node: close | The First Dirge
  *(The first dirge hums in your keeping — Singer Lhoris's masterwork and his act of buried defiance, the song commanded to walk the Faithless into the Wall that has secretly sung their names at every funeral for ten thousand years — and whether you decoded its second song, carried it to indict the Court, freed it to be re-sung kinder forever, restored its names to the graves, or left its secret sealed a while longer, you carry away the artist's deepest truth, which is the saga's: that beauty in the service of power can be made to smuggle the very truth that power means to bury, that a song is the one keeping the Wall can never file because it is never finished, and that the oldest dirge in the world was, all along, on the side of the dead it was written to mourn.)*
